:::summary
Benjamin Franklin (1706–1790) was printer, scientist, diplomat, philosopher, and Founding Father — perhaps the most versatile genius in American history, who harnessed lightning from the sky and persuaded France to save the Revolution, and whose self-made life became the archetypal American story of industry, wit, and practical wisdom.
